When I moved to Harare in 1985, issues of social justice were at the core of Zimbabwe's national health policy.
After the new government emerged from a long civil war, it immediately announced a socialist policy making healthcare services and primary education virtually free.
Massive rural health centers have made it possible for 80% of the population to reach one within walking distance of two hours - a truly remarkable advancement.
In the year of Zimbabwe's independence in 1980, 22% of children received routine vaccinations.
By 1990, just a decade later, this proportion had risen to 80%.
I am honored to be part of this transformation, this revolution.
Excitement and comradeship were genuine.
Working shoulder-to shoulder with outstanding Zimbabweans, scientists, doctors, activists, I feel part of not just an African liberation struggle, but a progressive global public health movement.
I have faced daunting challenges.
In 1980, the year I arrived, Zimbabwe reported its first AIDS case.
In the early 1980s, I had seen several AIDS patients while undergoing medical training at Harlem Hospital, but... we never imagined encountering anything like this in Africa.
When I arrived there, the infection rate was around 2%.
This proportion rapidly increased, when I left Harare 18 years later, one in four adults were infected.
By the mid-1990s, I had told hundreds of vibrant young people that their HIV tests were positive.
I witnessed colleagues and friends dying, as did my students and hospital patients.
Facing this situation, my colleague and I opened a clinic.
We demonstrate how to use condoms.
We promote awareness in schools and workplaces.
We conduct research, providing advice on how partners of HIV-infected individuals can protect themselves.
We worked very hard at all of this, and I believe that at the time I was doing everything I could.
I provided the best treatment possible under the circumstances at that time.
However, I did not make constructive changes.
Former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan had once candidly acknowledged that it was his personal failure that led to the Rwandan genocide.
In 1994, he was the head of the UN peacekeeping department.
At the ten-year memorial ceremony for the genocide, he recounted how he believed he had done everything possible at the time, but it was was only after the genocide that I realized there were so many things that I could have done and should have done, to raise the alarm and seek support.
The outbreak of AIDS caught medical organizations off guard. The World Health Organization estimates that three million nine hundred thousand people have died from this disease today. Many, like myself, feel regret and sorrow for not having been able to prevent it sooner.
But when I lived in Zimbabwe, I didn't realize I was an advocate or a political figure.
I thought I was going there because to my medical knowledge, due to my clinical and infectious disease research.
I always felt that my job was to care for patients, through research to better understand the characteristics of the population affected by the virus, and I hoped to slow its spread.
I realized that the proportion of marginalized groups infected and dying of AIDS was alarmingly high.
In sugarcane plantations, these places more akin to feudal domains than modern enterprises, 60% of pregnant women tested positive for HIV.
My role is to demonstrate to people that being infected is not a moral failing, but it is related to machismo and tied to forced labor and colonialism.
The majority of whites remained unscathed.
As medical experts, our approaches are sadly inadequate: we plead with individuals to alter their personal behaviors, to use condoms, and to reduce the number of sexual partners.
The infection rate continued to rise, as treatment, while effective as our most powerful weapon against the virus, was unaffordable for the entire African public sector when it became feasible in Western countries.
I did not venture to assert that the inequity in access to life-saving medicines, or the issues within potential economic and political systems, were the driving forces behind such high rates of infection across such large populations.
I justified my silence by reminding myself that I was merely a visitor in this country, and sounding the alarm might lead to deportation, hindering my ability to do my work, care for my patients, and conduct the critical research that was needed.
So, I did not boldly criticize the government's early HIV policies.
I did not express my concerns loudly enough.
Many doctors and health workers might feel that I have not gone too far.
Our commitment to our patients is sacred and inviolable, akin to the Hippocratic Oath and its various iterations, forming the foundation of the doctor-patient relationship.
I gave my utmost to every patient.
Yet, I know that the infectious diseases that arise from the fractures in our society reflect more than just biological phenomena; they are reflections of exclusion, intolerance, racism, gender bias, and class discrimination.
