Medical anthropologists, such as Paul Farmer, who works on HIV/AIDS in Haiti, refers to this as structural violence. Structurally, because inequality is rooted in the political and economic organization of our societies, often ignored by those in power and privilege; violently, because its impacts, like premature death, suffering, and disease, are violent in nature.
We have done little for the sick if we are not aware of these social injustices.
Ringing the alarm bell is the first step in guiding public health in the right direction, this is how we seek support, to break through and create genuine ways of change.
So now, I am no longer silent.
I've been outspoken on many matters, though it may be uncomfortable for both the listener and myself.
Much of this has to do with apartheid and organized racism - things that should not have happened in this country, things that should not exist in medical practice or in public health.
However, they do exist, at the cost of shortened lives.
This is why the echoes of racism's toll on public health resonate in America, continuously fueled by institutionalized, interpersonal acts of violence against people of color, deeply intertwined with our tragic history - 255 years of slavery, 91 years of segregation, 61 years of inadequate attempts at equality. It is my work as Commissioner of Health in New York City that focused on these alarms.
In New York City, the premature mortality rate, or dying before the age of 65, was 55% higher for Black individuals compared to White individuals.
In 2012, black women faced over 10 times the risk of death related to pregnancy compared to white women.
Despite the significantable progress we've made in reducing infant mortality, the birth-to-first-year mortality rate for Black infants is is still nearly three times that of White infants.
New York City is not an exception.
These statistics are similar across the entire United States.
A recent New York Times analysis reports that there are approximately fifteen million missing black men across the nation.
The author points out that among, among, between the ages of 25 and 54, at least one in six black men has been lost to the shadows of daily life, incarceration, or premature death.
Young black people face disproportionately high levels of violence on a daily basis, which is incredibly unjust, all encapsulated in the recent protests waving the "Black Lives Matter" banner.
However, we must remember the state of ordinary medicine and its outcomes, along with the persistent and disproportionately high rates of illness - heart disease, cancer, diabetes, HIV/AIDS - the diseases that quietly and slowly consume lives, taking more black lives prematurely.
As the "Black Lives Matter" movement unfolded, I felt frustrated and angry, hesitant and reluctant within medical institutions, in my research, and even in the use of the term "racism."
Every time I say it, you probably already feel it.
Medical students in their white coats, marching to protest chemical weapons, yet medical establishments largely stand idly by the ongoing effects of racial discrimination on health conditions and mortality rates.
I'm concerned that the trend towards personalized and precise medications, seeking biological and genetic targets for better-designed therapies, might inadvertently distract us from the bigger picture - the everyday scenes where one lives, grows, works, and loves, profoundly impacting population health for many of us, ill-health.
Living our daily lives, as healthcare workers, whether in clinics or conducting research, we bear witness to immense injustices. We see the homeless, unable to follow medical advice, prioritizing more pressing matters; the young transgender, planning suicide, due to society's cruelty; the single mother, compelled to feel responsible for her child's ill-health.
As healthcare professionals, our role is not just treating our patients but but sounding the alarm and advocating for change.
And regardless of its validity, our social positions lend credibility to our voices, and we should not squander it.
I am remorseful for not being forthright about this in Zimbabwe. I have committed to myself, as the Health Commissioner of New York City, to utilize every opportunity to sound the alarm and advocate for health equity.
I speak out against racism, and I hope you will join me, and I'll join you when you speak out against sexism, or any form of inequality.
It's time for us to stand together against structural inequalities - to speak out boldly.
We don't need to have all the answers to advocate for change.
All we need is courage.
Our patients' health, our own health, depends on this.
